\subsection*{(a) Dragging the Box}

When the box is dragged, the horizontal component of the force \( F \) is \( F \cos \theta \) and the vertical component (upward) is \( F \sin \theta \) as shown in Fig. 2.19. The reaction force \( N \) on the box by the floor will be:

\begin{equation}
N = mg - F \sin \theta
\end{equation}

\subsection*{(b) Equation of Motion for Dragging}

The equation of motion will be:

\begin{align}
ma &= F \cos \theta - \mu N \\
   &= F \cos \theta - \mu (mg - F \sin \theta) \\
\therefore a &= \frac{F}{m} (\cos \theta + \mu \sin \theta) - \mu g
\end{align}

\subsection*{(c) Pushing the Box}

When the box is pushed, the horizontal component of the force \( F \) will be \( F \cos \theta \) and the vertical component \( F \sin \theta \) (downwards), as shown in Fig. 2.20. The reaction force exerted by the floor on the box will be:

\begin{equation}
N' = mg + F \sin \theta
\end{equation}

which is seen to be greater than \( N \) (the previous case). The equation of motion will be:

\begin{align}
ma' &= F \cos \theta - \mu N' \\
    &= F \cos \theta - \mu (mg + F \sin \theta) \\
\therefore a' &= \frac{F}{m} (\cos \theta - \mu \sin \theta) - \mu g
\end{align}

A value which is less than \( a \) (the previous case). It therefore pays to pull rather than push at an angle with the horizontal. The difference arises due to the smaller value of the reaction in pulling than in pushing. This fact is exploited in handling a manual road roller or mopping a floor, which is pulled rather than pushed.

