\subsection*{First Method}

The center of mass of the hanging part of the chain is located at a distance $\frac{L}{6}$ below the edge of the table, as shown in Fig. 2.21. The mass of the hanging part of the chain is $\frac{M}{3}$. The work done to pull the hanging part onto the table is given by:

\[
W = Mg \cdot \frac{L}{6} \cdot \frac{1}{3} = \frac{MgL}{18}
\]

\subsection*{Second Method}

We can obtain the same result by calculus. Consider an element of length $dx$ of the hanging part at a distance $x$ below the edge. The mass of the length $dx$ is $\frac{M}{L} dx$. The work required to lift the element of length $dx$ through a distance $x$ is:

\[
dW = \frac{M}{L} \cdot g \cdot x \cdot dx
\]

The work required to lift the entire hanging part is:

\[
W = \int dW = \int_0^{L/3} \frac{Mg}{L} x \, dx
\]

Evaluating the integral, we find:

\[
W = \frac{Mg}{L} \left[ \frac{x^2}{2} \right]_0^{L/3} = \frac{Mg}{L} \cdot \frac{(L/3)^2}{2} = \frac{MgL}{18}
\]

